Location: Portland, Multnomah County, Oregon
Author Remarks:
Single "kek" followed by a rapid series.  This is a brief recording of a bird as it called from near the top of a deciduous tree in a residential neighborhood in Southwest Portland, Oregon.  I heard a second Cooper's Hawk calling in the distance, a few hundred feet behind me, but I don't think it can be heard on the recording.

I had not yet located the hawk visually as I was making this recording.  However shortly thereafter, a Scrub-Jay appeared, apparently in response to the hawk's call.  I then spotted the hawk as it took off away from me in pursuit of the jay.

Location: Salem, Polk, Oregon
Author Remarks:
Recording level was normalized, no filtering applied. Used equipment - Tascam DR-100 with unidirectional built-in microphone. Some echo could be caused by parallel walls surrounding the recording location.

Female was sitting in the middle of dense bush (2m from the ground) between two houses and producing series of clicking sounds. 

This female visiting my feeder, located in 9 feet (3m) from bush mentioned above, many times every day at least for one month before this record was made. This is the first time, when I've noticed such a behavior. Male of the same species was humming around while female was singing.

Photo were taken right before the recording: <http://www.flickr.com/photos/bushman_k/10600919896/>

Author Remarks:
Western Wood-Pewee, giving the call typically only heard on their wintering grounds.

-EDIT
I was originally not 100% confident of the ID, but it was confirmed as such the next day.  Thanks Eric and Jay!

Original note:
This is either a  Western Wood-Pewee (Contopus sordidulus) or Eastern Wood-Pewee (Contopus virens).  
I recorded it as it called from the top of a tall tree, in the evening just before sunset.
Western is far more likely at this location, however the call seems atypical for this species.  I have heard Eastern Wood-Pewees which gave a call similar to this.  I am soliciting opinions as to whether this vocalization is within the range of variation of Western Wood-Pewee.

Location: Philomath, Benton County, Oregon
Author Remarks: Empidonax. Small, active empid in alder next to open clearing in mixed woodland. Frequently flicked wings and tail up together. White eye ring prominent behind eye. Lower mandible orange with dark tip. Pale grey throat. Breast drab, belly yellow - markedly so when seen in shade, but barely visible when in sun. Thick whitish wingbars. Slight contrast between grey-toned head and olive-toned mantle. Repeated little "whit" or "tyip" calls. Initially suspected to be a Dusky, based in part on habitat, but Doug Robinson put me right.

Location: Fremont National Forest (near  Lakeview), Lake County, Oregon
Author Remarks:
This is intermediate between Pacific-Slope Flycatcher (Empidonax difficilis) and Cordilleran Flycatcher (Empidonax occidentalis).  There is considerable confusion locally as to the identities of many east-of-the-Cascades "Western" flycatchers, such as this, where neither parent species is found in a pure form.

This recording is the audio track extracted from video, recorded on a Samsung Galaxy S4 phone.  It is otherwise unedited.

Edit: Thanks for the informative comments, Andrew!  I decided to list this under Pacific-Slope Flycatcher so that it may be found in search results, though as [Andrew Rush](http://www.xeno-canto.org/forum/topic/9325) points out, it is very likely genetically admixed and intermediate in song between Pacific-Slope and Cordilleran flycatchers.

Location: Klamath County, Oregon
Author Remarks: adult male Phainopepla, first known occurance in Klamath County, Oregon. First heard while conducting point count survey. I did not see the bird. Returned approx. one-half hour later and saw the bird atop a large yellow-flowering elderberry bush/small tree. It was preening and seemingly easily approachable. I took photos at first. Returned with fLIP camera and made one recording. I observed at close range its black plumage, crest, and red irises. An Anna's Hummingbird vocalized nearby. The habitat was an open large Oregon White Oak and grass area with pioneering Western Juniper which still left the area open. I did not note the smaller brush. It preferred the elderberry, but rested atop most prominent tops of small to medium sized bushes, shrubs, and trees.  It vocalized quite often, and seemed to have the same amount of time vocalizing as periods of silence. It did not sing, but its vocals were only the single note whistles as heard on this recording. I was in the vicinity a total of about 45 minutes including the point count time and relocating effort time.

Location: Newport, Lincoln County, Oregon
Author Remarks: Recording not modified; it was taken with a canon powershot sx20. After being photographed on the ground the day before, this skylark was flushed twice this morning in the same area (8am) and again several times at about 1pm. This recording was taken on the second time that it was flushed during that 1pm episode. It circled around for about two minutes (that's a rough guess), and the distance from me to the bird varied significantly during this recording (it came closer, got further, came closer, etc.). Habitat was sand dunes with extensive non-native beach grass.

Location: Deschutes County, Oregon
Author Remarks:
Extremely quiet "whisper song" recorded from a bird singing <30m directly above me, immediately following unusual copulation event. Two individuals observed in act of copulation. Bird on top "dismounted" and sat very closely beside bird on the bottom. Then the bird formerly on bottom jumped on top and started copulating, this time with the positions reversed! This second copulation was briefer and less coordinated, but still appeared to be a copulation attempt. 

After this head-scratching event, both birds separated and one began to sing this VERY quiet, fast and repetitive whisper song. It is unclear which of the two copulating individuals was the one vocalizing. 

Recorded on an iPhone 6. 12dB high pass filter at 1000kHz, 24dB low pass filter at 5000kHz, 10dB amplification.

Location: Reedsford Road, Myrtle Point, Coos County, Oregon
Author Remarks:
Recorded as video with a Nikon D3400 DSLR camera and converted to mp3 and amplified using *Audacity*. There is a domestic guinea fowl calling in the foreground obscuring the grosbeak calls. There is one clear grosbeak call note after the 0:04 timestamp.

There was a flock of 9 grosbeaks (mixed male and female) in a tree along the Coquille River bank. They were calling from the tree in the recording and continued to call as they flew off.
